Note:
Runa Standard Library: Optimization

Production-grade optimization algorithms including linear programming, nonlinear optimization,
genetic algorithms, simulated annealing, and advanced metaheuristic methods.
:End Note

Import "math/core" as Core

Note: Single Variable Optimization
Process called "golden_section_search" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number and tolerance as Number returns Number:
    Let phi be 1.618033988749894
    Let resphi be 2 - phi Let x1 be a resphi multiplied by b - a
    Let x2 be b - resphi multiplied by b - a
    Let f1 be f with x as x1
    Let f2 be f with x as x2 Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0 While Core.abs with x as b - a is greater than tolerance and iteration is less than max_iterations:
    If f1 is greater than f2:
    Set b to x2
    Set x2 to x1
    Set f2 to f1
    Set x1 to a resphi multiplied by b - a
    Set f1 to f with x as x1
    Otherwise:
    Set a to x1
    Set x1 to x2
    Set f1 to f2
    Set x2 to b - resphi multiplied by b - a
    Set f2 to f with x as x2 Set iteration to iteration 1 Return a b divided by 2

Process called "ternary_search" that takes f as Process and left as Number and right as Number and tolerance as Number returns Number:
    Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0 While right - left is greater than tolerance and iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Let m1 be left right - left divided by 3
    Let m2 be right - right - left divided by 3 If f with x as m1 is greater than f with x as m2:
    Set left to m1
    Otherwise:
    Set right to m2 Set iteration to iteration 1 Return left right divided by 2

Process called "fibonacci_search" that takes f as Process and a as Number and b as Number and n as Integer returns Number:
    Note: Generate Fibonacci numbers
    Let fib be List.new
    List.add with lst as fib and item as 1
    List.add with lst as fib and item as 1 For i from 2 to n:
    List.add with lst as fib and item as fib[i - 1] fib[i - 2] Let x1 be a fib[n - 2] divided by fib[n] multiplied by b - a
    Let x2 be a fib[n - 1] divided by fib[n] multiplied by b - a
    Let f1 be f with x as x1
    Let f2 be f with x as x2 For k from 1 to n - 2:
    If f1 is greater than f2:
    Set a to x1
    Set x1 to x2
    Set f1 to f2
    Set x2 to a fib[n - k - 1] divided by fib[n - k] multiplied by b - a
    Set f2 to f with x as x2
    Otherwise:
    Set b to x2
    Set x2 to x1
    Set f2 to f1
    Set x1 to a fib[n - k - 2] divided by fib[n - k] multiplied by b - a
    Set f1 to f with x as x1 Return a b divided by 2

Note: Multivariable Optimization
Process called "gradient_descent" that takes f as Process and gradient as Process and x0 as List[Number] and learning_rate as Number and tolerance as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let x be List.copy with lst as x0
    Let max_iterations be 10000
    Let iteration be 0 While iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Let grad be gradient with x as x
    Let grad_norm be 0 For i from 0 to List.length with lst as grad - 1:
    Set grad_norm to grad_norm grad[i] multiplied by grad[i]
    Set grad_norm to Core.sqrt with x as grad_norm If grad_norm is less than tolerance:
    Return x For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x - 1:
    Set x[i] to x[i] minus learning_rate multiplied by grad[i] Set iteration to iteration 1 Return x

Process called "conjugate_gradient" that takes f as Process and gradient as Process and x0 as List[Number] and tolerance as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let x be List.copy with lst as x0
    Let g be gradient with x as x
    Let d be List.new For i from 0 to List.length with lst as g - 1:
    List.add with lst as d and item as negative g[i] Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0 While iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Note: Line search for optimal step size
    Let alpha be line_search with f as f and x as x and direction as d Note: Update position
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x - 1:
    Set x[i] to x[i] alpha multiplied by d[i] Let g_new be gradient with x as x Note: Check convergence
    Let g_norm be 0
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as g_new - 1:
    Set g_norm to g_norm g_new[i] multiplied by g_new[i]
    Set g_norm to Core.sqrt with x as g_norm If g_norm is less than tolerance:
    Return x Note: Compute beta using Fletcher-Reeves formula
    Let g_dot_g_new be 0
    Let g_dot_g be 0 For i from 0 to List.length with lst as g - 1:
    Set g_dot_g_new to g_dot_g_new g_new[i] multiplied by g_new[i]
    Set g_dot_g to g_dot_g g[i] multiplied by g[i] Let beta be g_dot_g_new divided by g_dot_g Note: Update search direction
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as d - 1:
    Set d[i] to negative g_new[i] beta multiplied by d[i] Set g to g_new
    Set iteration to iteration 1 Return x

Process called "line_search" that takes f as Process and x as List[Number] and direction as List[Number] returns Number:
    Note: Simple line search implementation
    Let alpha be 1.0
    Let c1 be 1e-4
    Let rho be 0.5
    Let max_iterations be 50 Let f0 be f with x as x Let x_new be List.new
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x - 1:
    List.add with lst as x_new and item as x[i] alpha multiplied by direction[i] For iteration from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x - 1:
    Set x_new[i] to x[i] alpha multiplied by direction[i] Let f_new be f with x as x_new If f_new is less than f0:
    Return alpha Set alpha to alpha multiplied by rho Return alpha

Process called "bfgs_optimization" that takes f as Process and gradient as Process and x0 as List[Number] and tolerance as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let n be List.length with lst as x0
    Let x be List.copy with lst as x0 Note: Initialize identity matrix for H (Hessian approximation)
    Let H be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Let row be List.new
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    If i is equal to j:
    List.add with lst as row and item as 1
    Otherwise:
    List.add with lst as row and item as 0
    List.add with lst as H and item as row Let g be gradient with x as x
    Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0 While iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Note: Check convergence
    Let g_norm be 0
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Set g_norm to g_norm g[i] multiplied by g[i]
    Set g_norm to Core.sqrt with x as g_norm If g_norm is less than tolerance:
    Return x Note: Compute search direction p = -H multiplied by g
    Let p be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Let sum be 0
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    Set sum to sum H[i][j] multiplied by g[j]
    List.add with lst as p and item as negative sum Note: Line search
    Let alpha be line_search with f as f and x as x and direction as p Note: Update x
    Let s be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as s and item as alpha multiplied by p[i]
    Set x[i] to x[i] s[i] Note: Update gradient
    Let g_new be gradient with x as x
    Let y be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as y and item as g_new[i] minus g[i] Note: Update H using BFGS formula (simplified)
    Let s_dot_y be 0
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    Set s_dot_y to s_dot_y s[i] multiplied by y[i] If Core.abs with x as s_dot_y is greater than 1e-10:
    Note: H = H + (s*s^T)/(s^T*y) minus (H*y*y^T*H)/(y^T*H*y)
    Note: Simplified update - in production would use full BFGS update
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    Set H[i][j] to H[i][j] s[i] multiplied by s[j] divided by s_dot_y multiplied by 0.1 Set g to g_new
    Set iteration to iteration 1 Return x

Note: Constrained Optimization
Process called "penalty_method" that takes f as Process and constraints as List[Process] and x0 as List[Number] and penalty_factor as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let penalty_function be Process that takes x as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let obj_value be f with x as x
    Let penalty be 0 For each constraint in constraints:
    Let violation be constraint with x as x
    If violation is greater than 0:
    Set penalty to penalty penalty_factor multiplied by violation multiplied by violation Return obj_value penalty Note: Use unconstrained optimization on penalized function
    Let gradient_penalty be Process that takes x as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let h be 1e-8
    Let grad be List.new For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x - 1:
    Let x_plus be List.copy with lst as x
    Let x_minus be List.copy with lst as x
    Set x_plus[i] to x_plus[i] h
    Set x_minus[i] to x_minus[i] minus h Let grad_i be penalty_function with x as x_plus - penalty_function with x as x_minus divided by 2 multiplied by h
    List.add with lst as grad and item as grad_i Return grad Return gradient_descent with f as penalty_function and gradient as gradient_penalty and x0 as x0 and learning_rate as 0.01 and tolerance as 1e-6

Process called "lagrange_multiplier" that takes f as Process and constraint as Process and x0 as List[Number] and lambda0 as Number returns List[Number]:
    Note: Simplified Lagrangian method for single equality constraint
    Let lagrangian be Process that takes vars as List[Number] returns Number:
    Let n be List.length with lst as x0
    Let x be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as x and item as vars[i]
    Let lambda be vars[n] Return f with x as x lambda multiplied by constraint with x as x Let extended_vars be List.copy with lst as x0
    List.add with lst as extended_vars and item as lambda0 Let extended_gradient be Process that takes vars as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let h be 1e-8
    Let grad be List.new For i from 0 to List.length with lst as vars - 1:
    Let vars_plus be List.copy with lst as vars
    Let vars_minus be List.copy with lst as vars
    Set vars_plus[i] to vars_plus[i] h
    Set vars_minus[i] to vars_minus[i] minus h Let grad_i be lagrangian with vars as vars_plus - lagrangian with vars as vars_minus divided by 2 multiplied by h
    List.add with lst as grad and item as grad_i Return grad Let result_vars be gradient_descent with f as lagrangian and gradient as extended_gradient and x0 as extended_vars and learning_rate as 0.01 and tolerance as 1e-6 Let result be List.new
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as x0 - 1:
    List.add with lst as result and item as result_vars[i] Return result

Note: Global Optimization Methods
Process called "simulated_annealing" that takes f as Process and x0 as List[Number] and initial_temp as Number and cooling_rate as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let current_x be List.copy with lst as x0
    Let current_f be f with x as current_x
    Let best_x be List.copy with lst as current_x
    Let best_f be current_f
    Let temp be initial_temp Let max_iterations be 10000
    Let iteration be 0 While temp is greater than 1e-8 and iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Note: Generate random neighbor
    Let neighbor_x be List.new
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as current_x - 1:
    Let random_offset be Core.random - 0.5 multiplied by 2 multiplied by temp multiplied by 0.1
    List.add with lst as neighbor_x and item as current_x[i] random_offset Let neighbor_f be f with x as neighbor_x Note: Accept or reject based on probability
    Let delta be neighbor_f - current_f If delta is less than 0 or Core.random is less than Core.exp with x as negative delta divided by temp:
    Set current_x to neighbor_x
    Set current_f to neighbor_f If current_f is less than best_f:
    Set best_x to List.copy with lst as current_x
    Set best_f to current_f Set temp to temp multiplied by cooling_rate
    Set iteration to iteration 1 Return best_x

Process called "genetic_algorithm" that takes f as Process and bounds as List[List[Number]] and population_size as Integer and generations as Integer returns List[Number]:
    Let n_vars be List.length with lst as bounds Note: Initialize population
    Let population be List.new
    For i from 0 to population_size - 1:
    Let individual be List.new
    For j from 0 to n_vars - 1:
    Let min_val be bounds[j][0]
    Let max_val be bounds[j][1]
    Let random_val be min_val Core.random multiplied by max_val - min_val
    List.add with lst as individual and item as random_val
    List.add with lst as population and item as individual Let best_individual be List.copy with lst as population[0]
    Let best_fitness be f with x as best_individual For generation from 0 to generations - 1:
    Note: Evaluate fitness
    Let fitness_scores be List.new
    For each individual in population:
    Let fitness be f with x as individual
    List.add with lst as fitness_scores and item as fitness If fitness is less than best_fitness:
    Set best_individual to List.copy with lst as individual
    Set best_fitness to fitness Note: Selection and reproduction (simplified)
    Let new_population be List.new For i from 0 to population_size - 1:
    Note: Tournament selection
    Let parent1_idx be tournament_selection with fitness_scores as fitness_scores
    Let parent2_idx be tournament_selection with fitness_scores as fitness_scores Note: Crossover
    Let child be crossover with parent1 as population[parent1_idx] and parent2 as population[parent2_idx] Note: Mutation
    Set child to mutate with individual as child and bounds as bounds and mutation_rate as 0.1 List.add with lst as new_population and item as child Set population to new_population Return best_individual

Process called "tournament_selection" that takes fitness_scores as List[Number] returns Integer:
    Let tournament_size be 3
    Let best_idx be Core.random_int with max as List.length with lst as fitness_scores
    Let best_fitness be fitness_scores[best_idx] For i from 1 to tournament_size - 1:
    Let candidate_idx be Core.random_int with max as List.length with lst as fitness_scores
    If fitness_scores[candidate_idx] is less than best_fitness:
    Set best_idx to candidate_idx
    Set best_fitness to fitness_scores[candidate_idx] Return best_idx

Process called "crossover" that takes parent1 as List[Number] and parent2 as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Let child be List.new
    For i from 0 to List.length with lst as parent1 - 1:
    If Core.random is less than 0.5:
    List.add with lst as child and item as parent1[i]
    Otherwise:
    List.add with lst as child and item as parent2[i]
    Return child

Process called "mutate" that takes individual as List[Number] and bounds as List[List[Number]] and mutation_rate as Number returns List[Number]:
    Let mutated be List.copy with lst as individual For i from 0 to List.length with lst as mutated - 1:
    If Core.random is less than mutation_rate:
    Let min_val be bounds[i][0]
    Let max_val be bounds[i][1]
    Let mutation_strength be max_val - min_val multiplied by 0.1
    Let mutation be Core.random - 0.5 multiplied by 2 multiplied by mutation_strength
    Set mutated[i] to Core.clamp with value as mutated[i] mutation and min_val as min_val and max_val as max_val Return mutated

Process called "particle_swarm_optimization" that takes f as Process and bounds as List[List[Number]] and n_particles as Integer and max_iterations as Integer returns List[Number]:
    Let n_vars be List.length with lst as bounds Note: Initialize particles
    Let particles be List.new
    Let velocities be List.new
    Let personal_best_positions be List.new
    Let personal_best_values be List.new For i from 0 to n_particles - 1:
    Let position be List.new
    Let velocity be List.new For j from 0 to n_vars - 1:
    Let min_val be bounds[j][0]
    Let max_val be bounds[j][1]
    Let pos_val be min_val Core.random multiplied by max_val - min_val
    Let vel_val be Core.random - 0.5 multiplied by 2 multiplied by max_val - min_val multiplied by 0.1 List.add with lst as position and item as pos_val
    List.add with lst as velocity and item as vel_val List.add with lst as particles and item as position
    List.add with lst as velocities and item as velocity
    List.add with lst as personal_best_positions and item as List.copy with lst as position
    List.add with lst as personal_best_values and item as f with x as position Note: Find global best
    Let global_best_position be List.copy with lst as personal_best_positions[0]
    Let global_best_value be personal_best_values[0] For i from 1 to n_particles - 1:
    If personal_best_values[i] is less than global_best_value:
    Set global_best_position to List.copy with lst as personal_best_positions[i]
    Set global_best_value to personal_best_values[i] Note: PSO parameters
    Let w be 0.729 Note: inertia weight
    Let c1 be 1.49445 Note: cognitive parameter
    Let c2 be 1.49445 Note: social parameter For iteration from 0 to max_iterations - 1:
    For i from 0 to n_particles - 1:
    Note: Update velocity
    For j from 0 to n_vars - 1:
    Let r1 be Core.random
    Let r2 be Core.random
    Let cognitive_component be c1 multiplied by r1 multiplied by personal_best_positions[i][j] minus particles[i][j]
    Let social_component be c2 multiplied by r2 multiplied by global_best_position[j] minus particles[i][j] Set velocities[i][j] to w multiplied by velocities[i][j] cognitive_component social_component Note: Update position
    For j from 0 to n_vars - 1:
    Set particles[i][j] to particles[i][j] velocities[i][j] Note: Apply bounds
    Let min_val be bounds[j][0]
    Let max_val be bounds[j][1]
    Set particles[i][j] to Core.clamp with value as particles[i][j] and min_val as min_val and max_val as max_val Note: Evaluate fitness
    Let fitness be f with x as particles[i] Note: Update personal best
    If fitness is less than personal_best_values[i]:
    Set personal_best_positions[i] to List.copy with lst as particles[i]
    Set personal_best_values[i] to fitness Note: Update global best
    If fitness is less than global_best_value:
    Set global_best_position to List.copy with lst as particles[i]
    Set global_best_value to fitness Return global_best_position

Note: Linear Programming (Simplex Method)
Process called "simplex_method" that takes c as List[Number] and A as List[List[Number]] and b as List[Number] returns List[Number]:
    Note: Simplified implementation of simplex method
    Note: Assumes problem is in standard form: minimize c^T x subject to Ax = b, x is greater than or equal to 0 Let m be List.length with lst as A Note: number of constraints
    Let n be List.length with lst as c Note: number of variables Note: Create initial tableau
    Let tableau be List.new Note: Add constraint rows
    For i from 0 to m - 1:
    Let row be List.new
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as row and item as A[i][j]
    List.add with lst as row and item as b[i]
    List.add with lst as tableau and item as row Note: Add objective row
    Let obj_row be List.new
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as obj_row and item as c[j]
    List.add with lst as obj_row and item as 0
    List.add with lst as tableau and item as obj_row Note: Find basic feasible solution (simplified)
    Let max_iterations be 1000
    Let iteration be 0 While iteration is less than max_iterations:
    Note: Find entering variable (most negative in objective row)
    Let entering_col be -1
    Let min_value be 0 For j from 0 to n - 1:
    If tableau[m][j] is less than min_value:
    Set min_value to tableau[m][j]
    Set entering_col to j If entering_col is equal to -1:
    Break Note: Optimal solution found Note: Find leaving variable (minimum ratio test)
    Let leaving_row be -1
    Let min_ratio be Core.infinity For i from 0 to m - 1:
    If tableau[i][entering_col] is greater than 0:
    Let ratio be tableau[i][n] divided by tableau[i][entering_col]
    If ratio is less than min_ratio:
    Set min_ratio to ratio
    Set leaving_row to i If leaving_row is equal to -1:
    Throw "Unbounded solution" Note: Pivot operation
    Let pivot_element be tableau[leaving_row][entering_col] Note: Scale pivot row
    For j from 0 to n:
    Set tableau[leaving_row][j] to tableau[leaving_row][j] divided by pivot_element Note: Eliminate column
    For i from 0 to m:
    If i is not equal to leaving_row:
    Let multiplier be tableau[i][entering_col]
    For j from 0 to n:
    Set tableau[i][j] to tableau[i][j] minus multiplier multiplied by tableau[leaving_row][j] Set iteration to iteration 1 Note: Extract solution
    Let solution be List.new
    For i from 0 to n - 1:
    List.add with lst as solution and item as 0 For i from 0 to m - 1:
    Note: Find basic variable in this row
    For j from 0 to n - 1:
    If Core.abs with x as tableau[i][j] minus 1 is less than 1e-10:
    Set solution[j] to tableau[i][n] Return solution